T1  - Asymmetric Adaptability: Dynamic Team Structures as One-Way Streets
AU  - Moon, Henry
AU  - Hollenbeck, John R.
AU  - Humphrey, Stephen E.
AU  - Ilgen, Daniel R.
AU  - West, Bradley
AU  - Ellis, Aleksander P.J.
AU  - Porter, Christopher O. L. H.
Y1  - 2004/10/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/20159611
DO  - 10.5465/20159611
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 681
EP  - 695
VL  - 47
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study tested whether teams working on a command and control simulation adapted to structural change in the manner implied by contingency theories. Teams shifting from a functional to a divisional structure showed better performance than teams making a divisional-to-functional shift. Team levels of coordination mediated this difference, and team levels of cognitive ability moderated it. We argue that the static logic behind many contingency theories should be complemented with a dynamic logic challenging the assumption of symmetrical adaptation.
AB  - This study tested whether teams working on a command and control simulation adapted to structural change in the manner implied by contingency theories. Teams shifting from a functional to a divisional structure showed better performance than teams making a divisional-to-functional shift. Team levels of coordination mediated this difference, and team levels of cognitive ability moderated it. We argue that the static logic behind many contingency theories should be complemented with a dynamic logic challenging the assumption of symmetrical adaptation.
